<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,798,1074]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Only one species is known in this genus. Described originally from a single female found in 
<collectingCountry box="[1218,1373,798,822]" name="New Zealand" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
, both sexes and larvae of 
<taxonomicName box="[378,510,835,859]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Karphothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dugdalei">
<emphasis box="[378,510,835,859]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">K. dugdalei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been taken from the leaves of the common sword grass, 
<taxonomicName box="[1225,1309,835,859]" class="Liliopsida" family="Cyperaceae" genus="Gahnia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1225,1309,835,859]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Gahnia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, at various sites across southern 
<collectingCountry box="[389,494,870,894]" name="Australia" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Australia</collectingCountry>
, between Tasmania and Albany in Western 
<collectingCountry box="[985,1088,870,894]" name="Australia" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Australia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Mound" box="[1103,1260,870,894]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" refString="Mound, L. A. (2002) Thrips and their host plants: new Australian records (Thysanoptera: Terebrantia). Australian Entomologist, 29, 49 - 60." type="journal article" year="2002">
Mound, 
<number box="[1199,1260,870,894]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). This is a slen- der, yellow species, with a long head superficially similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[835,975,907,931]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Aptinothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[835,975,907,931]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Aptinothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, but with slender wings that lack a discal seta on the clavus, and prosternal basantra that bear one or two pairs of setae. The tergal campaniform sensilla are close to the posterior margin, as in 
<taxonomicName box="[640,815,979,1003]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Bregmatothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[640,815,979,1003]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Bregmatothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but no craspeda are developed (
<figureCitation box="[1183,1267,978,1002]" captionStart="FIGURES 46 – 51" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1328,1351]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,195,1306]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,195,1306]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 46 – 51. Grass living Thripinae. (46) Karphothrips dugdalei, tergites VII – IX. Kranzithrips mareebai 47 – 51: (47) tergites VII – IX; (48) meso &amp; metanota; (49) sternites V – VI; (50) male tergites VII – IX; (51) head &amp; pronotum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/200573/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Fig. 
<number box="[1236,1267,978,1002]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="46.0">46</number>
</figureCitation>
), antennal segment I lacks dorso-apical setae, tergite IX of females has very short median dorsal setae, and the males have a single round pore plate medially on the third sternite.
</paragraph>
